  "reasoning": "I need to research the Federal Reserve's overnight repurchase agreements data. Let me start by gathering information.The FRED series is `RPONTSYD`. Let me get the historical data.Excellent data. Let me now analyze this carefully. The data shows this series is overwhelmingly near zero on most days, with occasional large spikes (especially at quarter-end and month-end). Let me run a detailed analysis.The data only goes through Feb 2, 2026 — the Feb 10 value hasn't been published yet. Let me now save my key finding and write the meta-reflection.Now let me provide my final forecast.\n\n## Summary\n\nThis question asks about the FRED series RPONTSYD — the daily value of overnight repo operations where the Fed purchases Treasury securities. \n\n**Key finding:** Feb 10, 2026 is the **second Tuesday of February**, and the data reveals an extremely consistent pattern: the second Tuesday of each month almost always has a value of ~$0.1 billion (100 million). This held for 9 of 12 months in my sample, with the remaining 3 showing near-zero values. The most recent second Tuesday (Jan 13, 2026) confirmed the pattern at 0.102.\n\nThe distribution is extremely non-Gaussian — essentially a mixture of:\n- **~15%** near-zero (the operation doesn't happen)\n- **~75%** at ~0.1B (the regular second-Tuesday operation)\n- **~10%** in a wide right tail (unexpected funding stress)\n\nBy January 2026, repo operations had returned to normal after the Oct-Dec 2025 stress period (which saw values up to 31.5B). Current conditions appear calm.",
